Wireless Equivalent Privacy (WEP) is an older encryption algorithm used to keep the data transmitted across a network secure. An advantage to using WEP is that it will be made clear to the user that they are not welcome because they will be discourage from connecting because they do not have the key required. WEP is used by several generations of devices so this means people will not need to worry during their network connection. However there are several disadvantages to using WEP such as a proficient hacker being able to hack your WEP key within a few minutes and intercept all the information coming in and out of the network. WiFi Protected Access 2  (WPA2) is a security measure that is used to protect wireless networks. It has been said that the main advantage of WPA2 is not hackable while WPA is. This itself is a great disadvantage to companies or users that have WPA2 encryption because it keeps all their networks safe and secure. However all this protection comes at a price as WPA2 requires much more processing power to do all this than WPA does meaning high loads will force you to rethink your security options. Finally we looked at Service Set Identifiers (SSID) which is a 32 alphanumeric character unique identifier which is attached to the header of packets sent over a WLAN. This can be split into 2.4 and 5GHz which is one of the main advantages as you can control who uses either one of these. This is ideal depending on the device and what they can actually support whether it is 2.4 or 5GHz. A disadvantage of using SSID is that whenever you configure a new device to join the network you must allocate it an SSID which becomes very complex if you decide to use both 2.4 and 5 GHz. \
